  "issue_number": 15,
  "issue_title": "reload() leaves the app dead with no recovery when startInternal() fails",
  "issue_body": "### Describe the bug\n\n## Summary\n\n`BaseDevServerStart.reload()` runs `stopInternal()` (which shuts down the old app thread and closes the old classloader) and then `startInternal()` (which prepares the proxy for a new generation, installs the new classloader, and starts the user's `main()` on a fresh thread). If `startInternal()` throws partway through \u2014 proxy worker re-creation fails, the new main class can't be loaded, a startup hook throws, etc. \u2014 the proxy server (Undertow listener / gRPC server) is still up, but no app thread is running. The reload exception bubbles up, but **the dev server never recovers automatically**: subsequent requests either receive a 500/404 from `ReloadHandler` and then quietly fall through to proxying-into-the-void, or they trigger another `reload()` that finds nothing changed and returns null. The user has to manually `Ctrl-C` and re-run `liveReload`.\n\n## Repro\n\nIn an sbt project on this branch, register a startup hook that throws on its second invocation (e.g., a counter inside an `RestApiHealthCheckStartupHook` subclass):\n\n1. `liveReload` \u2014 first request succeeds, app boots.\n2. Edit a source file to trigger a reload.\n3. Second `startInternal()` invokes the hook, which throws.\n4. `ReloadHandler.handleRequest` catches the exception, returns 500.\n5. Third request: `DevServerReloader.reload()` sees `changed=false`, `forceReloadNextTime=false`, `currentApplicationClassLoader != null`, returns null. `BaseDevServerStart.reload()` returns false. `ReloadHandler` then calls `next.handleRequest` which tries to proxy into `localhost:<httpPort>` \u2014 but no app is listening, so the response is `ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED` / `502`.\n\nFrom the user's perspective the dev server has become a dead-letter proxy with no clue why, no logs after the original stack trace, and no path back except a manual restart.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`core/build-link/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/BaseDevServerStart.java`, `reload()`:\n\n```java\npublic boolean reload() {\n  var reloadResult = buildLink.reload();\n  if (reloadResult instanceof ReloadGeneration casted) {\n    logger.info(\"\ud83d\udd03 Reloading an application\");\n    stopInternal();        // commits state: appThread=null, old classLoader closed\n    startInternal(casted); // \u2190 may throw; no recovery\n    logger.debug(\"Finished reloading\");\n    return true;\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\n`startInternal()`:\n\n```java\nprotected synchronized void startInternal(ReloadGeneration generation) {\n  if (!isRunning.get()) throw new UnrecoverableException(...);\n  prepareServerForNewGeneration();             // \u2190 XnioWorker / gRPC channel refresh\n  this.classLoader = generation.getReloadedClassLoader();\n  this.appThread = new Thread(...);\n  appThread.start();\n  runHooks(appThread, classLoader, startupHooks);   // \u2190 may throw\n}\n```\n\nIf `prepareServerForNewGeneration()` or `runHooks(...)` throws (or the `new Thread(...)`-launched main throws synchronously into a hook via `stopInternal()`-from-app-thread), the state-mutating side effects of `startInternal()` have only been partially applied: `appThread` may be set but its `main()` already exited, `classLoader` may be set but the app didn't initialize, etc. `reload()` has no rollback. `DevServerReloader.reload()` has already advanced past its dirty bits (`changed=false`, `forceReloadNextTime=false`, `currentApplicationClassLoader=<new>`) so it won't volunteer another attempt.\n\n## Test plan\n\n- [x] Build: `./gradlew :core:build-link:compileJava :core:runner:compileJava :core:webserver:compileJava :core:webserver-grpc:compileJava :gradle:compileKotlin` on JDK 17, plus `spotlessCheck`.\n- [ ] `sbt test` against sbt 1.x and 2.x \u2014 should remain green.\n- [ ] `./gradlew :gradle:check` (functional tests) \u2014 should remain green.\n- [ ] Manual repro per the Repro section, both before and after the fix: confirm that after a failing reload, a subsequent request retries `buildLink.reload()` and either succeeds (if the underlying issue resolved) or surfaces the error again, instead of silently proxying into nothing.\n\n## Compatibility\n\n`BuildLink` gains a `default` method (`requestReload()` no-op). All three plugin sites already wire a `BuildLink` via the runner \u2014 they don't need changes. No DSL keys added or removed.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n_No response_\n\n### Operating system\n\nNone\n\n### Build System\n\nNone\n\n### Version of jvm-live-reload\n\n0.1.1\n\n### JDK Version\n\n17.0.18\n\n### Extra context or search terms\n\n_No response_",
